(a) Protect the capital;
(b) Ensure the overall monetary base is always fully backed by highly liquid US dollar assets;
(c) Ensure sufficient liquidity to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(d) Pursue investment returns within the bounds of the above (a) to (c) to safeguard the Fund’s long-term purchasing power.

- Understanding the valuation procedures for different classes of financial assets and liabilities, including relevant monitoring controls;
- Evaluating and testing the effectiveness of monitoring controls, including automated systems and related application controls;
- Confirming the existence, rights and obligations, and completeness of financial assets and liabilities through third-party confirmations;
- Verifying quoted prices from independent sources when using market quotations;
- When valuation techniques with observable market data are used, assessing the appropriateness of the valuation techniques and the reasonableness of the assumptions, and verifying the parameters with independent sources; and
- When valuation techniques with non-observable market data are used, assessing the appropriateness of the valuation techniques, and the reasonableness of the assumptions and parameters.

- Obtaining and reviewing valuation reports for investment properties held directly by the Group or through associates or joint ventures, and verifying that the fair values are based on the valuations stated in the reports;
- Evaluating the independence and qualifications of the valuer; and
- Assessing whether the valuation methods are appropriate and whether the assumptions and parameters are reasonable.

- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement due to fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks; and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence as a basis for my opinion. Because fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omissions, misrepresentations, or override of internal controls, the risks of not detecting material misstatement due to fraud are higher than those due to error;
- Understand internal controls relevant to the audit to design appropriate procedures, but not to express an opinion on the effectiveness of internal controls;
- Evaluate whether the accounting policies adopted by the Financial Management Officer are appropriate, and whether the related disclosures and estimates are reasonable;
- Determine whether the use of the going concern basis of accounting is appropriate, and, based on the audit evidence obtained, assess whether there are significant uncertainties related to events or conditions that may cast significant doubt on the Group’s ability to continue as a going concern. If I conclude that there is significant uncertainty, I will include appropriate disclosures in my auditor’s report. If disclosures are inadequate, I will issue a modified auditor’s report. My conclusions are based on audit evidence obtained up to the date of my auditor’s report; future events or conditions may cause the Group to cease to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including disclosures, and whether they provide a true and fair reflection of transactions and events; and
- Obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of entities or business activities within the Group to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for directing, supervising, and performing the Group’s audit. I bear full responsibility for my audit opinion.
